e, "mention": "C", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9944983124732971, "span": {"begin": 824, "end": 825}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:61696"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Pro-Gly-NH2", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9978252053260803, "span": {"begin": 836, "end": 847}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:25555"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "N", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999693751335144, "span": {"begin": 891, "end": 892}}, {"id": ["mesh:C058050"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "pGlu-His-Trp-Ser", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9846216440200806, "span": {"begin": 903, "end": 919}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3814"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "kisspeptin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9945453405380249, "span": {"begin": 1001, "end": 1011}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2796"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GnRH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9977235198020935, "span": {"begin": 1052, "end": 1056}}], "text": "Kisspeptin is a key signalling neuropeptide hormone in mammals and some other vertebrates. The kisspeptin gene (KISS1) encodes a 145 amino acid prepolypeptide that is converted to 4 active peptides with names based on the number of amino acids (kisspeptin-54, 14, 13, 10); each active peptide is able to activate kisspeptin receptor (GPR54, KISS1R) because of a conserved c-terminal region Arg-Phe-NH2 group (Hu et al. 2018).&nbsp;Kisspeptin is released by the anteroventral periventricular nucleus (AVPV) region of the hypothalamus, and binds kisspeptin receptors (GPR54, KISS1R) on Gonadotropin-releasing hormone neurons. &nbsp;   Gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is produced by the hypothalamus. &nbsp;Gonadotropin-releasing hormone is a peptide hormone composed of 10 amino acids (Hassanein et al. 2024). &nbsp;The C terminal (Pro-Gly-NH2) is involved in receptor binding, with the N-terminal (pGlu-His-Trp-Ser) involved in receptor activation (Hassanein et al. 2024). &nbsp; &nbsp;Decreased kisspeptin results in decreased levels of released GnRH. &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:19:45 +0000 2026"}